<p>DataLogManager also fails this scenario. If the roboRIO has been shutdown neatly so that it has  a valid /etc/timestamp, it will sometimes create files with a filename that corresponds to a time near what was recorded in /etc/timestamp.</p>
<p>Will post an issue against allwpilib.</p>
<p>Have a workaround; blow away /etc/natinst/share/timestamp.</p>","post_number":7,"post_type":1,"posts_count":9,"updated_at":"2023-03-03T16:46:13.409Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":42,"readers_count":41,"score":8.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":428487,"topic_slug":"how-to-tell-when-date-time-are-correct-on-roborio","display_username":"fovea1959","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":13575,"username":"Peter_Johnson","name":"Peter Johnson","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/peter_johnson/{size}/10417_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":15648,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Herder of 3620 Programmers / LRI / CSA"},"post_url":"/t/how-to-tell-when-date-time-are-correct-on-roborio/428487/7","custom_user_title":"Herder of 3620 Programmers / LRI / CSA","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3156594,"name":"fovea1959","username":"fovea1959","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/fovea1959/{size}/5301_2.png","created_at":"2023-03-03T17:07:46.763Z","cooked":"<p>The test for year&gt;2000 is what is keeping most people from hitting this. The one second is not enough for the time change to percolate through, but DataLogManager is disbelieving dates &lt; 2000.01.01, which is what it sees on a roboRIO that has never been shutdown neatly.</p>","post_numb